A noun (or pronoun) referred to an object or affected by a verb.
A noun (or pronoun) receives a direct object affected by transitive verb (typically as a recipient)
Mom bakes [_Robert=(indirect object)_] a cake=(direct object).
She bounces [_him=(indirect object)_] the ball=(direct object).
The postman delivers [_us=(indirect object)_] mail=(direct object).
The boy kicks [_her=(indirect object)_] the ball=(direct object).

Dad gave [_David=(indirect noun)_] the keys=(direct object).

These pronouns are used to form the subject of a sentence or as a predicate noun (aka predicate nominative) when following a form of be verb (e.g., is, was) and it renames or describes the subject of the sentence.
Subjective pronouns include: I, you, he, she, it, we, they.
I wash pots and pans in the [_sink_].
I put dirty dishes in the [_dishwasher_].
I keep cold items in the [_refrigerator_].
I warm up leftovers in the [_microwave_] [_oven_].
Objective pronouns are used as direct objects, indirect objects or objects of the preposition.
Objective pronouns include: me, you, him, her, it, us, them.
Possessive pronouns are used to indicate ownership of objects.
Possessive pronouns include: my, your, his, hers, its, our, ours, their, theirs.
